Abstract¶

In this project, we decided to look at twitter tweets about Comcast and see if there was a reflection on the stock prices. Our hypothesis is that the Comcast community spirit is dull compared to other companies and their stock price reflects this downfall in this time of financial crisis. Using scrapped data from Twitter, we looked at whether the sentiment of people on twitter would affect the stock prices. We scraped twitter for the tweets about comcast and then made visual plots to see if the stocks could be predicted by the feelings of twitter user.

Description of the Data¶

Scrapers Used¶

We used data that we scrapped from Twitter for a period of 24 weeks using a Twitter scrapper that did not require a Twitter API.

Data Description¶

The data we used for this assignment is data we scrapped from Twitter and a financial dataset about Comcast stocks. The twitter data included information such as hashtags, unique identifiers for the tweet, the text of the tweet, the name of the person who tweeted, the username of the person who tweeted, the location of the user, the description in the user's bio, the number of followers, the number of friends, the number of lists, the total number of tweets per user, and the date that the account was made.

When and How Long Twitter Was Scraped¶

We scraped Twitter on April 28th and 29th for 4 hours each day. The twitter data dated back to the previous 24 weeks.

Alternative Data Source(s) Used¶

The alternative data source that we used is a data set of the financial set for comcast. We also found data on the location of each comcast center.

def username_tweets_to_csv(username, count):
    # Creation of query object
    tweetCriteria = got.manager.TweetCriteria().setUsername(username)\
                                            .setMaxTweets(count)
    # Creation of list that contains all tweets
    tweets = got.manager.TweetManager.getTweets(tweetCriteria)

    # Creating list of chosen tweet data
    user_tweets = [[tweet.date, tweet.text] for tweet in tweets]

    # Creation of dataframe from tweets list
    tweets_df = pd.DataFrame(user_tweets, columns = ['Datetime', 'Text'])

    # Converting dataframe to CSV
    tweets_df.to_csv('{}-{}k-tweets.csv'.format(username, int(count/1000)), sep=',')

def text_query_to_csv(text_query, count):
    # Creation of query object
    tweetCriteria = got.manager.TweetCriteria().setQuerySearch(text_query)\
                                                .setMaxTweets(count)
    # Creation of list that contains all tweets
    tweets = got.manager.TweetManager.getTweets(tweetCriteria) # GetOldTweets3.models.Tweet.Tweet object
    # Can access the following aspects of a tweet as instance variables
    #    'author_id', 'date', 'favorites', 'formatted_date', 'geo', 'hashtags', 'id', 'mentions', 
    #    'permalink', 'replies', 'retweets', 'text', 'to', 'urls', 'username'
    
    # switch on debugger by uncommenting the following
    # from IPython.core.debugger import Pdb as pdb;    pdb().set_trace() #breakpoint; dont forget to quit
    # Creating list of chosen tweet data
    text_tweets = [[tweet.date, tweet.text, tweet.hashtags] for tweet in tweets]

    # Creation of dataframe from tweets
    tweets_df = pd.DataFrame(text_tweets, columns = ['Datetime', 'Text', 'hashtags'])

    # Converting tweets dataframe to csv file
    tweets_df.to_csv(f'{"_".join(text_query.split())}_{int(count/1000)}k_tweets.csv')

def process_tweet(tweet):  
    d = {}
    d['hashtags'] = [hashtag['text'] for hashtag in tweet['entities']['hashtags']]
    d['id'] = tweet['id']
    d['text'] = tweet['text']
    d['name'] = tweet['user']['name']
    d['user'] = tweet['user']['screen_name']
    d['user_loc'] = tweet['user']['location']
    d['user_desc'] = tweet['user']['description']
    d['user_followers'] = tweet['user']['followers_count']
    d['user_friends'] = tweet['user']['friends_count']
    d['user_listed'] = tweet['user']['listed_count']
    d['user_created'] = tweet['user']['created_at']
    d['user_favs'] = tweet['user']['favourites_count']
    d['user_statuses'] = tweet['user']['statuses_count']

    return d

def text_query_to_csv(text_query, count):
    # Creation of query object
    tweetCriteria = got.manager.TweetCriteria().setQuerySearch(text_query)\
                                                .setMaxTweets(count)
    # Creation of list that contains all tweets
    tweets = got.manager.TweetManager.getTweets(tweetCriteria) # GetOldTweets3.models.Tweet.Tweet object
    # Can access the following aspects of a tweet as instance variables
    #    'author_id', 'date', 'favorites', 'formatted_date', 'geo', 'hashtags', 'id', 'mentions', 
    #    'permalink', 'replies', 'retweets', 'text', 'to', 'urls', 'username'
    
    # switch on debugger by uncommenting the following
    # from IPython.core.debugger import Pdb as pdb;    pdb().set_trace() #breakpoint; dont forget to quit
    # Creating list of chosen tweet data
    text_tweets = [[tweet.date, tweet.text, tweet.hashtags] for tweet in tweets]

    # Creation of dataframe from tweets
    tweets_df = pd.DataFrame(text_tweets, columns = ['Datetime', 'Text', 'hashtags'])

    # Converting tweets dataframe to csv file
    tweets_df.to_csv(f'{"_".join(text_query.split())}_{int(count/1000)}k_tweets{start_of_week}.csv', mode = "a")

def get_tweet_vector(tweet):
    got3_columns = ['formatted_date', "author_id",  "username",  "geo", "text", "hashtags", 'mentions', 
                "to", "urls",  
                'replies', 'retweets',  "favorites", 'permalink']
    return [tweet.hashtags, tweet.author_id, tweet.username, tweet.geo, tweet.text, tweet.hashtags, 
     tweet.mentions, tweet.to, tweet.urls, tweet.replies, tweet.retweets, tweet.favorites, tweet.permalink]
                     

def get_tweet_result(text_query = 'comcast', since_date = '2019-11-01', 
                     until_date = '2019-04-28', count = 2000):
    # Creation of query object
    tweetCriteria = got.manager.TweetCriteria()\
                               .setQuerySearch(text_query) \
                               .setSince(since_date)\
                               .setUntil(until_date)\
                               .setMaxTweets(count)
    # Creation of list that contains all tweets
    tweets = got.manager.TweetManager.getTweets(tweetCriteria)
    # Creating list of chosen tweet data

    got3_columns = ['formatted_date', "author_id",  "username",  "geo", "text", "hashtags", 'mentions', 
                    "to", "urls",  
                    'replies', 'retweets',  "favorites", 'permalink']
                         #    'author_id', 'date', 'favorites', 'formatted_date', 'geo', 'hashtags', 
                         # 'id', 'mentions', 
        #    'permalink', 'replies', 'retweets', 'text', 'to', 'urls', 'username'

    text_tweets = [[tweet.formatted_date, tweet.author_id, tweet.username, 
                    tweet.geo, tweet.text, tweet.hashtags, 
                    tweet.mentions, tweet.to, tweet.urls, tweet.replies, tweet.retweets, 
                    tweet.favorites, tweet.permalink] for tweet in tweets]                     
    tweets_df = pd.DataFrame(text_tweets, columns=['formatted_date', "author_id",  "username",  "geo", "text", "hashtags", 'mentions', 
                    "to", "urls",  
                    'replies', 'retweets',  "favorites", 'permalink'])
    filename = f'{"_".join(text_query.split())}_{int(count/1000)}k_tweets{start_of_week}.csv'
    tweets_df.to_csv(filename, mode = "a", header=False, index=False)
    print(filename)

import time
from random import seed
from random import randint
# seed random number generator
seed(1)
from datetime import date, datetime, timedelta

def datespan(startDate, endDate, delta=timedelta(days=7)):
    currentDate = startDate
    while currentDate < endDate:
        yield currentDate
        currentDate += delta
        
text_query = "comcast"
start_of_period = date(2019, 11, 1)
end_of_period   = date(2020, 4, 28)
start_of_week = start_of_period
week_plus_1_start = start_of_period + timedelta(days=7)

# scrape the tweets on weekly basis (timedelta(days=7))
#
for i, week_plus_1_start in enumerate(datespan(week_plus_1_start, end_of_period, delta=timedelta(days=7))):
    print(f"week {i}, start of week: {start_of_week} {week_plus_1_start}")
    get_tweet_result(text_query = text_query, since_date = f"{start_of_week}", 
                 until_date = f"{week_plus_1_start}", count = 2000)  
    time.sleep(randint(20, 90)) #suspends (waits) execution of the current thread for a given number of seconds

    start_of_week = week_plus_1_start

def sentiment_bins(data):
    if data <= -0.5:
        grouping = 'Strong-Negative'
    elif data > -0.5 and data < 0.0:
        grouping = 'Mild-Negative'  
    elif data > 0.0 and data < 0.5:
        grouping = 'Mild Positive'
    elif data >=0.5:
        grouping = 'Strong-Positive'
    else:
        grouping = 'Neutral'
    return grouping

comcast_df['sentimentLabel'] = comcast_df['PolarityScore'].apply(sentiment_bins)

In [26]:
def importance_score(data):
    '''Importance of tweets is calculated here based on the amount of favorites that the tweet
    received. The numbers were calculated based on the statistics for the apple twitter data file.
    The number of followers is not taken into account.'''
 
    if data == 0:
        grouping = '1'
    elif data > 0 and data <= 1:
        grouping = '2'
    elif data > 1 and data <= 4:
        grouping = '3'
    elif data > 4 and data <= 49:
        grouping = '4'
    else:
        grouping = '5'
    return grouping

comcast_df['importanceLabel'] = comcast_df['favorites'].apply(importance_score)

Results¶

Our hypothesis that the Comcast community spirit is dull and their stock price reflects this downfall was not shown through the data analysis we did on the tweets we scraped from Twitter and the stock prices that we got from yahoo finance.

None of the visuals that we have made can be used to prove our hypothesis, which leads us to conclude that our hypothesis is incorrect.

Conclusion¶

Based on the geoplot that we created, any conclusion that we get from this data can only be applied to the eastern side of the United States. This is the area where the majority of comcast centers operate in. According to our correlation matrix, the most highly correlated variablse are the number of favorites, retweets, and replies. This makes sense, as the more that a tweet is favorites or retweeted, the more people will see it and reply to it. This shows that our importance metric did not need other factors, as the other columns that we had considered using were most correlated with favorites, which is what we did end up using. We also made a correlation matrix on the comcast stock data, but the correlation seemed to be the same for every column except volume, so we were not able to make a conclusion based off of this.

Our sentiment by importance bar chart shows that the majority for each importance level had a sentiment of neutral, which makes sense because it is difficult for the code that we used to find all positive or negative feelings in each text of a tweet. The second most popular was mild positive, which was interesting to us because, according to our hypothesis, we expected most tweets about comcast to be negative, as their stock price has been decreasing. The other categories of sentiment did not have a big different between each importance level of tweets.

Our last graph is a scatter plot based on polarity versus stock prices, grouped by months. We filtered our data to only included tweets of the highest level of importance, and found that the average polarity was just a little above 0 for each month, and did not have a trend either positive or negative. This is shown in our scatterplot, as the points do not have any pattern and are found all over the graph. On the other hand, the comcast stock prices clearly have a negative trend, as the scatterplot points for their stock price decrease each month.

In conclusion, there is no correlation between the opinion of popular tweets about comcast on twitter and the price of their stock. This is proven by our data, as the trend for stock price has consistently decreased in the past six months, whereas the polarity of the tweets about comcast on twitter has stayed about the same and has no consistent positive or negative trend.
